==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Massacre
<hw>Mas"sa*cre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. LL.
<ets>mazacrium</ets>; cf. Prov. G. <ets>metzgern</ets>,
<ets>metzgen</ets>, to kill cattle, G. <ets>metzger</ets> a butcher, and
LG. <ets>matsken</ets> to cut, hew, OHG. <ets>meizan</ets> to cut, Goth.
<ets>m⟦aacute⟧itan</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The killing of a
considerable number of human beings under circumstances of atrocity or
cruelty, or contrary to the usages of civilized people; <as>as, the
<ex>massacre</ex> on St. Bartholomew's Day; the St. Valentine's Day
<ex>massacre</ex>; the Amritsar <ex>massacre</ex>; the Wounded Knee
<ex>massacre</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Murder.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Massacre</er>, <er>Butchery</er>,
<er>Carnage</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Massacre</xex> denotes the
promiscuous slaughter of <xex>many</xex> who can not make resistance, or
much resistance. <xex>Butchery</xex> refers to cold-blooded cruelty in
the killing of men as if they were brute beasts. <xex>Carnage</xex>
points to slaughter as producing the heaped-up bodies of the
slain.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll find a day to <qex>massacre</qex> them all,⟦br⟧
And raze their faction and their family.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If thou delight to view thy heinous deeds,⟦br⟧
Brhold this pattern of thy <qex>butcheries</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such a scent I draw⟦br⟧
Of <qex>carnage</qex>, prey innumerable!</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massacre</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Massacre
<hw>Mas"sa*cre</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Massacred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Massacring</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>massacrer</ets>. See <er>Massacre</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<def>To kill in considerable numbers where much resistance can not be
made; to kill with indiscriminate violence, without necessity, and
contrary to the usages of nations; to butcher; to slaughter; -- limited
to the killing of human beings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If James should be pleased to <qex>massacre</qex> them all, as
Maximian had <qex>massacred</qex> the Theban legion.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Massacrer</ent>⟦br⟧
